        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance Gradation 3 acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Primary QoI is the clinical decision variable (NIH). Validation experiment measures the same QoI using the same damage accumulation model. Mechanistic linkage between secondary QoIs (velocity, WSS) and NIH documented in model description. Pass."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "Validation activities were conducted on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry at the same five operating points defined in the COU. The experimental fluid (blood analog with matched viscosity and density) and boundary conditions replicate the VAD operating envelope. No extrapolation of validation evidence beyond the COU domain is required.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/ac/validation-relevance-gradation3",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation activity relevance Gradation 3 acceptance criteria",
        "description": "Validation geometry: identical to COU geometry (FDA generic centrifugal pump). Operating points: all five COU points validated. Fluid: blood analog matched to within viscometry uncertainty. No extrapolation required. Pass."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error as a separately tracked credibility factor applies specifically to iterative solver convergence residuals in implicit time-stepping schemes where solver tolerance contributes non-trivially to solution error distinct from discretization error. In this steady-state RANS simulation, iterative convergence is monitored via residual drop to 1e-6 and confirmed via solution change between iterations < 0.01% for all QoIs. Solver convergence error is subsumed within the discretization error factor (assessed at Gradation 4 with GCI bounding), which already accounts for all numerical approximation errors in the converged solution. Treating numerical solver error as a separate factor would double-count error already captured in the GCI analysis. This factor is therefore not applicable to this specific computational approach and is documented as such per ASME V&V 40 Section 5.3.2 guidance on factor scoping."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Use error as a standalone credibility factor addresses analyst-induced errors arising from misapplication of general-purpose software to a problem outside its validated domain, or from incorrect setup by inexperienced users. This assessment is conducted by the FDA CDRH Computational Modeling Group using a purpose-built, locked simulation workflow with automated boundary condition ingestion from the experimental dataset and mandatory peer review of all case setups. The workflow was developed specifically for this pump geometry and has been independently audited. Analyst use error is effectively controlled at the process level through the SQA factor (assessed at Gradation 3) and the locked workflow, leaving no residual use-error pathway that is not already captured. Separate scoring of this factor would not add discriminating credibility information and is therefore marked not-applicable per the project's factor scoping plan."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty as a separately assessed credibility factor is applicable when multiple competing model forms (e.g., RANS turbulence closures, constitutive models) have been identified and their relative bias quantified. In this COU, the model form — SST k-ω RANS with Carreau-Yasuda non-Newtonian viscosity and Giersiepen-Wurzinger power-law hemolysis accumulation — was fixed by the FDA benchmark protocol and is the only model form evaluated against the experimental data. There is no alternative model form in scope for this COU; model form selection uncertainty is acknowledged in the Monte Carlo UQ (included as an epistemic uncertainty contribution) but is not separately scored as a credibility factor because the benchmark protocol does not permit model form variation. This factor is therefore not applicable under the defined assessment scope."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model inputs as a distinct credibility factor is intended to assess uncertainty and sensitivity of simulation outputs to variability in input parameters such as material properties, geometry dimensions, and boundary condition values. In this package, input uncertainty is fully addressed through the Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification activity (1,000 Latin hypercube samples across all uncertain inputs: viscosity, density, hemolysis model coefficients, rotational speed, and flow rate), which propagates input uncertainty through to NIH prediction intervals. The Monte Carlo UQ results are directly linked to both ValidationResults and the SensitivityAnalysis object. Scoring model inputs as a separate credibility factor would duplicate the UQ evidence already captured and reported. This factor is therefore not applicable as a standalone assessment item; its substance is subsumed within the UQ documentation."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Test samples as a credibility factor addresses the representativeness and statistical adequacy of physical test specimens used in validation experiments — for example, whether the number of pump units tested is sufficient to characterize unit-to-unit manufacturing variation. The FDA benchmark PIV study used a single certified reference pump manufactured to tight geometric tolerances (surface finish Ra < 0.8 µm, dimensional tolerance ±0.05 mm) specifically to eliminate inter-unit variability as a confound. The COU also concerns a single reference geometry, not a production population. Statistical characterization of sample-to-sample variation is therefore outside the scope of both the validation experiment and the COU. This factor does not apply to single-unit reference geometry validation activities and is marked not-applicable accordingly."
    },
    {
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters is a credibility factor that evaluates whether the input parameters used in the simulation match those of the physical validation experiment — a concern when experiments are conducted at scaled conditions (e.g., reduced Reynolds number, surrogate fluids with different rheology) requiring similarity arguments to bridge to the COU. In this assessment, the CFD model uses exactly the same boundary conditions, geometry, fluid properties, and operating points as the FDA benchmark experiment without any scaling transformation or similarity argument. The experimental and simulation input parameter sets are identical by design (the benchmark protocol mandates this). There is therefore no equivalency gap to assess; this factor is not applicable when the simulation inputs are directly specified from experimental measurements without dimensional or physical transformation."
    }
  ],
  "sensitivityAnalysisDescription": "Monte Carlo sensitivity analysis (1,000 LHS samples) was performed varying six uncertain inputs — blood analog viscosity (±8%), hemolysis model exponent α (±12%), hemolysis model coefficient C (±15%), inlet flow rate (±2%), rotational speed (±0.5%), and outlet pressure (±3 mmHg) — to assess their relative contribution to NIH prediction uncertainty. Sobol first-order indices indicate hemolysis model coefficient C (S1 = 0.41) and exponent α (S1 = 0.33) dominate NIH variance; fluid viscosity contributes S1 = 0.14; remaining inputs collectively contribute S1 = 0.12. The 95th-percentile NIH prediction interval (0.0031–0.0078 g/100 L) remains below the clinical threshold of 0.01 g/100 L across all five operating points.",
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/decision/cou2-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/morrison/org/fda-cdrh-computational-modeling-group",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "All seven assessed credibility factors meet or exceed their required gradation levels at MRL 5: SQA (3/3), Code Verification (3/3), Discretization Error (4/3 — exceeds requirement), Test Conditions (3/3), Output Comparison (3/3), QoI Relevance (3/3), and Validation Activity Relevance (3/3). Six factors (Numerical Solver Error, Use Error, Model Form, Model Inputs, Test Samples, Equivalency of Input Parameters) are marked not-applicable with documented rationale explaining why each factor's substance is either subsumed within other assessed factors, controlled at the process level, or outside the scope of this single-geometry reference validation. The not-applicable designations do not represent credibility gaps; each is supported by a substantive rationale demonstrating that the underlying credibility concern is addressed through alternative means or is structurally absent from this COU. Monte Carlo UQ confirms the 95th-percentile NIH prediction interval (0.0031–0.0078 g/100 L) remains below the clinical threshold (0.01 g/100 L) with a safety margin of 22%. The provenance chain from raw PIV data through GCI analysis to validated hemolysis predictions is complete and traceable. The package is accepted for regulatory submission.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
